<td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Planet busters</span><hr size=1> A million megaton bomb would not destroy a planet. The Earth has been subjected to impacts of much greater energy than this many times in its history:<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.grc.nasa.gov/WWW/K-12/Numbers/Math/Mathematical_Thinking/asteroid_hit.htm"> Glenn Learning Center Exercise</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (I believe there is an error in this, since 30,000 miles per hour does not equal 10 km/sec, but the principle is well illustrated, and any impactor from interplanetary space would have to be moving at greater than escape velocity anyway.)<br>
This<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://athene.as.arizona.edu/~lclose/teaching/a204/lecture5.html"><br>
U Arizona lecture</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->also provides some useful data.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.badastronomy.com/bitesize/kaboom.html"><br>
Phil Plait's Doomsday calculator</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is a dandy device for calculating impact energies in megatons.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/18/02 12:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=33.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.ibiblio.org/wm/paint/auth/munch/munch.scream.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Planet busters</span><hr size=1> I agree.<br>
Past a certain limit, a nuclear device will simply blow a hole up thru the atmosphere. The surface will act as a reflector, bouncing the energy back up through the hole. (Not that nasty things would not result, but only that blowing up a planet isn't easy. Making it uninhabitable maybe, rubble no.)<br>
<br>
A crude rule of thumb is that a nuclear weapon will vaporize roughly the equal to its yield.<br>
<br>
Thus a one gigaton deeply buried device will very roughly vaporize a gigaton of rock.<br>
